node.text:
This is why certain companies pay dividends!⠀
⠀
Just because a company pays a dividend isn’t necessarily a good thing or a bad thing. Commonly, companies that do pay dividends are more established companies that’s price doesn’t vary much. On the other hand, companies that don’t pay dividends tend to be more high-growth stocks that might be a little more risky.⠀
⠀
The stock you choose should be based on the fundamentals of a company, not just if it pays a high dividend.⠀

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Making Cents of Finance on August 14, 2021 tagging @realethanlang. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Ethan Lang @realethanlang Why did you start investing? I'll go first like when my money makes money.'.

node.text:
It's the coolest thing to see your money make money.

I remember when I first started investing, I had about $200...

When my account value grew to $201 the next day, mannnnn, what I PUMPED.

My account didn't go up everyday, sure, but I knew that over time it would grow, so I added more money in every time I got money from working.

It's not about that I made $1... I mean c'mon, it's one dollar.

No, no, no. It was about the fact that this was scalable.

If I could make $1 off of $200, what could I do when I had $100,000 or $1 million.

I could live off of my investments.

I could still work (if I wanted to), but I didn't have to.

I would have the freedom to create the life that I wanted without feeling constrained.

Maybe you want that type of life too.

I'm telling you right now, if you even remotely resonate with that, just get started.

That's a huge hurdle for a lot of people to get over is just starting.

You don't need permission to start, but I give you that permission. START.

You might make mistakes along the way, but so do we all...

Just start and get yourself some education...

and that doesn't mean a college degree...

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Making Cents of Finance on August 12, 2021 tagging @realethanlang. May be an image of 1 person and text that says 'Ethan Lang @realethanlang Your job will never make you rich. Investing the money from your job to make more money will though.'.

node.text:
A high income is important. Don't get what I'm saying wrong.

However, if you have a high income, that's all it is... a high income.

You can't get rich off a high income alone. 

Having a high income certainly helps the cause if you're smart, but without investing some of your income, you'll have to continue working forever.

The sole purpose of investing is so that you can have your investments fund your lifestyle and cover your expenses.

You could be making $10 million a year, but if you spend all that money every year, you'll be left with NOTHING if you lose that job.

It's not about what you earn, it's about what you keep.

Yeah, it's easier to keep more if you earn more, but you still have to keep it. Just remember that.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Making Cents of Finance on August 10, 2021. May be an image of text that says '$ MAKING CENTS OF FINANCE @centsoffinance "The stock market it a device for transferring money from the impatient to the patient." -Warren Buffett'.

node.text:
Investing has become extremely popular over the past year.

Actually, I lied...

Fake investing has become popular over the past year.

I'm sorry, but picking a few stocks on Robinhood and selling them a week later really isn't investing...

I'm happy that people are getting intrigued with investing. TRUST ME.

I love talking about finance and investing with anyone.

But, I'm got into some many conversations about what stock should I pick?

Got any stocks that are gonna double in the next year?

What about weed stocks?

They just aren't the right questions to be asking. 

It should really be...

How can I enjoy today while also putting money away, so I can have freedom in my future?

Now, that's a lot more elaborate and deep of a questions, but damn, it's important.

Investing is amazing and getting a few stocks on Robinhood is great. I mean, it's a start, which is better than most people.

However, investing isn't about picking the stock that's going to up in the next 1-2 months.

It's about betting on the US stock market. It's about picking the companies that are going to perform well over the next two to three decades and holding over the long-term.

If you want to see the benefits of investing, you have to be willing to HOLD.

It's not about timing the market. It's about time in the market. There is a big difference in those two statements.

node.text:
Maybe I'll get some hate on this post, but I really think a lot of people are going to college that don't need it.

Now, background.

This is not coming from a 'college dropout' that's also an eNtRepRenEur.

I'm currently in college, and I plan on graduating with a degree.

HOWEVER,

I didn't go to some fancy university.

I went to a school where I can get a quality education without spending the extra $10,000 a year to help the college upkeep a nice campus.

I'm going to graduate steps ahead of the game because I'll be debt-free and money in investments working for me.

Now, there are some people that might need to go into debt for a degree, such as doctors and laywers.

However, that still doesn't mean they have to go to some fancy college either.

Just be smart about it. That's my two cents.

Now, some of you might already be done with school and have debt.

Don't dwell if you think you "made a mistake."

Just get smart about paying off that debt.

node.text:
Honestly, I've always been saying to hold a little bit of crypto.

a LITTLE bit.

For me, it's about 2% of my entire portfolio.

I never knew exactly knew how to explain that... 

I mean, if it's only two percent of your portfolio, why invest in it at all?

Well then, my guy @financejosh came out with this post, and I was like YAASSSS.

I couldn't have said it better myself.

If you want to invest in crypto, do it, but please don't stake your entire financial future on it.

Think about the people who did that with internet stocks in 2000...

Or the people who did that will real estate in 2008...

I'm not saying don't buy any, but don't buy TOO much.

Invest responsibly. 

Omg, that sounded like a beer commercial. Invest responsibly.

node.text:
Man, it's really all about the freedom for me...

and, you are probably just like me.

You want the freedom to do what you want, when you want.

I mean, that might not be the same thing for you and me, but it's all the same goal.

For example, I love camping, hiking, mountain biking, and all that wilderness shit.

I'm a modern day Bear Grylls for anyone who got that reference.

Okay, I'm really getting off topic...

For you, that might be something completely different.

It could be lying on a beach and sipping on some 'orange juice'.

It could being your kid's soccer coach.

It could be so you can binge some more netflix.

I'm not the one to tell you what you love to do.

You probably already know that by know.

However, I am telling you, you can begin to get that freedom by investing and building wealth to sustain your lifestlye.

It doesn't have to be lavash. I mean, there's not really anything lavish about going camping in a 50-year old camper...

Yes, I am renovating a 50-year old camper.

BUT, it's what I love.

So, figure out what you love, and start getting that freedom.
